<p>Different risks, at both levels, process level and financial statement level evaluate together with the controls relevant against the same, can be documented in the form of a RCM. It is a complete document, which captures at one place, for each business cycle.</p>

<p><strong>Here are several points to be discussed.</strong></p>

<ul>
	<li>The risks of material misstatement including the fraud risks and any other noteworthy risks that must be individually identified.</li>
	<li>The account balances affected against each of the risks recognized.</li>
	<li>The financial statement declaration that are made for each of the listed risks and accounts balances.</li>
	<li>The controls that are related to the each of the risks and assertions. A control may address more than one risk or assertion.</li>
	<li>The promptness of the control.</li>
	<li>Testing and reporting on the control and the document(s) that need to be prepared to evidence the exercise of the control.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Here are the illustrative formats of the Risk control matrix that shows the way of work we employ:</strong></p>

<ul>
	<li>Risk (what may go wrong?)</li>
	<li>Account balances affected</li>
	<li>Manual/Automated control</li>
	<li>Control type preventive/detective</li>
	<li>Explanation of control activity</li>
</ul>

<p>It should also address the liability, regularity, and documentary evidence. The frequency is needed to shown them separately.&nbsp;</p>

